        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-04-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-04-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="445"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d445">
                <head>445. Memorandum From President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="from"
                        >Nixon</persName> to his Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName
                        corresp="#p_KHA1" type="to">Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d445fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Subject Files, Box 341, <gloss target="#t_HAK1"
                            >HAK</gloss>/President Memos 1971–. No classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-04-27">April 27, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Moynihanʼs idea of buying the entire Turkish opium crowd is one that seems
                    intriguing. I realize there are problems here, but would you have a check made
                    to see what, if anything, could be done. <persName corresp="#p_CJBJ1"
                        >Connally</persName> seems to like the idea, provided it does not have other
                    foreign policy implications which would militate against it.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d445fn2">The idea was endorsed by Secretary of the Treasury
                            <persName corresp="#p_CJBJ1">Connally</persName> during an April 27
                        meeting with the President. (Memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_HBGAM1"
                            >Haig</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_SH2">Sonnenfeldt</persName>
                        and <persName corresp="#p_SH1">Saunders</persName>, April 28; ibid.)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
